body: Good afternoon. There is a 0-day privilege escalation exploit for the Use-after-Free vulnerability in the WIDFRD.sys driver. The exploit is implemented for Windows 10 x64 1607, 1703, 1709, 1803, 1809, 1903, 1909. It is present in 2004 and later, but the corresponding code in the driver was rewritten, and OS crashes in BSOD before the target vulnerability is triggered on null pointer dereferencing. There are some nuances on exploitation: not all systems may be vulnerable, as there is a dependency on hardware configuration. Exploitation takes place by disabling SMEP (CR4 modification), modifying PTE/PML4 if necessary, and executing code that performs token replacement of the target process with the system one. I publish the announcement here, because my regular customers do not need / do not fit, and in the personal from those who on the forum expressed a desire to buy, no one answers. The price of 60k, negotiable. Willing I can write and give a utility, which when run on the system of interest will tell if the OS is vulnerable or not. First contact in the LN, then in the jabber.{backslash}n{backslash}n{backslash}nDoing more:{backslash}n{backslash}nExploit sold in one hand.{backslash}n{backslash}nVideo of work:{backslash}n{backslash}nhttps://filetransfer.io/data-package/ctyCDTW6#link{backslash}n{backslash}nPassword bvdiviy2861rVJVl{backslash}n {backslash}n{backslash}n What happens in the video:{backslash}n{backslash}n1. The process wud.exe launches, exploiting the vulnerability.wud.exe creates the process cmd.exe and pauses for 5 seconds to check its privileges. I launch notepad.exe (instance 1) from the created console. After a while, I check my privileges and launch notepad.exe (instance 2). I check the level of cmd.exe and two instances of notepad.exe in Process Explorer. It looks like instance 1 is running with medium IL, and instance 2 (when cmd.exe's permissions were already elevated) with SYSTEM.
All in all, it's not that bad. Bots are coming, 4 nets took a chorus yesterday :)
